From: poirot@mickey.jsc.nasa.gov (Daniel Poirot)
Subject: Re: Any LINUX installations in real life environments?
Date: Thu, 25 Nov 1993 14:10:05 GMT

I am getting a lot out of Linux at work.  Our inventory follows...

        - three 486/33 machines setup for general purpose Unix 
          development and as X workstations.

        - two 386/16 machines working as network printer servers.

        - five tiny AMPRO [34]86 CPUs running as the distributed 
          'brain' of a new robot we are building in-house.

        - one 386/16 running control software for a pair of MICROBOT 
          TeachMover arms and a VOTRAX speech synthesizer.

In the next few days (?) I am planning on adding a 386 running Linux to
a Cybermotion robot base that currently has no on-board control CPU.

One of our robot vendors supportes Linux as the native operating system
on a base that they sell.  (We are currently running OS/2 on ours)

We make extensive use of software gathered from the Net.  We also have
ported network-based robotics communications software called TelRIP
that was developed at Rice University.

My opinion is that Linux is a stable system that provides a
U*ix-compatible, flexible alternative to commercial software running on
a variety of cheap hardware.

[Decend from cleansing substance container]

